[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Iterative development delivers a full system at the very beginning and then changes the functionality of each subsystem with each new release.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "iterative development delivers a full system at the very beginning and then changes the functionality of each subsystem with each new release.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, in a word processing package, iterative development would provide primitive forms of all types of functionality in Release 1, such as creating text and cutting and pasting, even if some functions are clumsy or slow initially.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "using iterative development, we would provide primitive forms of all three types of functionality in Release 1. For example, we can create text and then cut and paste it, but the cutting and pasting functions might be clumsy or slow.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Each subsequent release improves on the previous ones by enhancing the quality and usability of the functionality, such as making cutting and pasting easy and quick in Release 2.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "So in the next iteration, Release 2, we have the same functionality, but have enhanced the quality; now cutting and pasting are easy and quick. Each release improves on the previous ones in some way.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

