[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The ISO/IEC 25010 quality characteristics replace the older McCall quality factors by providing a more modern and structured model for software quality assessment.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "ISO 9126. In the early 1990s, the software engineering community attempted to consolidate the many views of quality into one model that could act as a worldwide standard for measuring software quality.The result was ISO 9126, a hierarchical model with six major attributes contributing to quality (International Standardization Organization 1991).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The ISO 9126 model, which evolved into ISO/IEC 25010, defines six major quality attributes that are strictly hierarchical and relate to the user view of software, unlike McCall's model which relates external quality factors to product quality criteria.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One major difference between the ISO model and those of McCall and Boehm is that the ISO hierarchy is strict: each right-hand characteristic is related only to exactly one left-hand attribute. Moreover, the right-hand characteristics are related to the user view of the software, rather than to an internal, developer view.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "McCall's quality model associates external quality factors with product quality criteria and measurements, focusing on both user and developer perspectives, while ISO/IEC 25010 focuses more on user-related characteristics.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "McCall associated each right-hand criterion with a measurement to indicate the degree to which an element of quality was addressed (McCall, Richards, and Walters 1977).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Moreover, the right-hand characteristics are related to the user view of the software, rather than to an internal, developer view.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The two models map to each other in that both attempt to relate external quality factors to measurable product attributes, but ISO/IEC 25010 provides a more structured and strict hierarchy, focusing on user-centric quality characteristics.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One major difference between the ISO model and those of McCall and Boehm is that the ISO hierarchy is strict: each right-hand characteristic is related only to exactly one left-hand attribute.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "McCall associated each right-hand criterion with a measurement to indicate the degree to which an element of quality was addressed (McCall, Richards, and Walters 1977).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

