[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The SOLID principles of object-oriented design are a set of design principles that help create more maintainable, understandable, and flexible software systems by reducing coupling and increasing cohesion.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The collection of software design principles grows as we 'encode' our collective experience and observations in new design advice. For example, Davis (1995) proposes 201 principles of software development, many of which are design related. In this book, we restrict our discussion to six dominant principles: modularity, interfaces, information hiding, incremental development, abstraction , and generality . Each seems to have stood the test of time and is independent of style and methodology.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Although the provided context does not explicitly list the SOLID principles by name, it discusses key design principles that align with the goals of SOLID principles, particularly focusing on reducing coupling and increasing modularity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Modularity , also called separation of concerns , is the principle of keeping separate the various unrelated aspects of a system, so that each aspect can be studied in isolation (Dijkstra 1982). ... If the principle is applied well, each resulting module will have a single purpose and will be relatively independent of the others; in this way, each module will be easy to understand and develop.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To determine how well a design separates concerns, we use two concepts that measure module independence: coupling and cohesion (Yourdon and Constantine 1978).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The principles that help reduce coupling in a software system include:",
        "citations": [],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Modularity: By decomposing a system into modules that encapsulate unrelated concerns, each module has a single purpose and is relatively independent, which reduces coupling between modules.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Modularity , also called separation of concerns , is the principle of keeping separate the various unrelated aspects of a system, so that each aspect can be studied in isolation (Dijkstra 1982). ... If the principle is applied well, each resulting module will have a single purpose and will be relatively independent of the others; in this way, each module will be easy to understand and develop.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Interfaces: Restricting modules to be responsible for only one function or activity minimizes the information passed between modules and simplifies interfaces, which reduces coupling.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "ch module to be  responsible  for  only  one  function  or  one  activity. This  restriction  minimizes  the amount of information that is passed to a controlled module, and it simplifies the module's interface to a fixed and recognizable set of parameters and return values.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Information Hiding: By encapsulating details within modules and exposing only necessary interfaces, modules become less dependent on each other's internal details, reducing coupling.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The collection of software design principles grows as we 'encode' our collective experience and observations in new design advice.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Abstraction: Using abstraction allows focusing on essential qualities rather than specific details, which helps in designing loosely coupled modules.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In this book, we restrict our discussion to six dominant principles: modularity, interfaces, information hiding, incremental development, abstraction , and generality .",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, the context explains that coupling is measured by how modules depend on each other, and the goal is to achieve low coupling, such as data coupling, which is simpler and less likely to be affected by changes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When complex data structures are passed between modules,we say there is stamp coupling between the modules; if only data values, and not structured data, are passed, then the modules are connected by data coupling . Stamp coupling represents a more complex interface between modules, because the modules have to agree on the data's format and organization.Thus, data coupling is simpler and less likely to be affected by changes in data representation.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In summary, the SOLID principles, through modularity, well-defined interfaces, information hiding, and abstraction, help reduce coupling by ensuring modules have single responsibilities, minimal and clear interfaces, and encapsulated internal details, leading to more maintainable and flexible software designs.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

