[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Static application security testing (SAST) involves analyzing the source code or components of a program before it is run, using tools such as code analyzers, structure checkers, data analyzers, and sequence checkers to detect syntax errors, structural flaws, data issues, and event sequence problems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Static Analysis. Several tools can analyze a source program before it is run. Tools that investigate the correctness of a program or set of components can be grouped into four types: 1. Code analyzer... 2. Structure checker... 3. Data analyzer... 4. Sequence checker...",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Dynamic application security testing (DAST), on the other hand, involves monitoring the program's behavior during execution, especially useful for systems with concurrent operations or real-time systems, by capturing snapshots of the program state and reporting on coverage of statements, paths, and branches.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Dynamic Analysis. Many times, systems are difficult to test because several parallel operations are being performed concurrently... Automated tools enable the test team to capture the state of events during the execution of a program by preserving a 'snapshot' of conditions. These tools are sometimes called program monitors because they watch and report the program's behavior.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "SAST should be applied early in the software development life cycle (SDLC), during the coding or implementation phase, to detect issues before the program runs, while DAST is applied during or after the program execution phase, such as during testing, to observe the program's runtime behavior and identify security vulnerabilities.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

