[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The concept of a \"Bounded Context\" in Domain-Driven Design (DDD) relates to the decomposition of a system into software units by defining clear boundaries within which a particular model applies, similar to how a system is decomposed into distinct software units or modules with well-defined interfaces in a layered architecture.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We say that a design is modular when each activity of the system is performed by exactly one software unit, and when the inputs and outputs of each software unit are well-defined. A software unit is well-defined if its interface accurately and precisely specifies the unit's externally visible behavior: each specified input is essential to the unit's function, and each specified output is a possible result of the unit's actions.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We want to decompose the system's design into its constituent programmable units, such as modules, objects, or procedures.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In layered architecture, the system is decomposed into layers and units that have clear responsibilities and interfaces, which aligns with the idea of bounded contexts that encapsulate specific domain models and their logic, preventing ambiguity and overlap between different parts of the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The best uses graph has a tree structure or is a forest of tree structures. In such a structure, every subtree is a subset of our system, so we can incrementally develop our system one software unit at a time. Each completed unit is a correct implementation of part of our system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The textbook recommends several machine learning techniques for automating effort estimation beyond the COCOMO II model.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In the past, most effort- and cost-modeling techniques have relied on algorithmic methods. That is, researchers have examined data from past projects and generated equations from them that are used to predict effort and cost on future projects. However, some researchers are looking to machine learning for assistance in producing good estimates.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The recommended machine learning techniques include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Neural networks, which represent interconnected units (neurons) corresponding to activities, and are trained with data from past projects to identify patterns and produce effort estimates.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, neural networks can represent a number of interconnected, interdependent units, so they are a promising tool for representing the various activities involved in producing a software product. In a neural network, each unit (called a neuron and represented by network node) represents an activity; each activity has inputs and outputs. Each unit of the network has associated software that performs an accounting of its inputs, computing a weighted sum; if the sum exceeds a threshold value, the unit produces an output. The output, in turn, becomes input to other related units in the network, until a final output value is produced by the network. Neural networks are developed by 'training' them with data from past projects. Relevant data are supplied to the network, and the network uses forward and backward algorithms to 'learn' by identifying patterns in the data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Regression trees, which have been used to produce predictions more accurate than the original COCOMO model and SLIM, though not as good as neural networks or function point models.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Srinivasan and Fisher (1995) used Kemerer's data (Kemerer 1989) with a statistical technique called a regression tree; they produced predictions more accurate than those of the original COCOMO model and SLIM, a proprietary commercial model.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Tree induction techniques, which have been shown to produce better results using datasets like Kemerer and COCOMO.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Briand, Basili, and Thomas (1992) obtained better results from using a tree induction technique, using the Kemerer and COCOMO datasets.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Decision trees, which can identify project, process, and product characteristics useful in predicting effort and fault-prone modules.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Porter and Selby (1990) also used a tree-based approach; they constructed a decision tree that identifies which project, process, and product characteristics may be useful in predicting likely effort. They also used the technique to predict which modules are likely to be fault-prone.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Case-Based Reasoning (CBR), which builds a decision algorithm based on combinations of inputs encountered on projects, deals only with actual events, and is easier for users to understand than neural networks or rule chains.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A machine-learning technique called Case-Based Reasoning (CBR) can be applied to analogy-based estimates. Used by the artificial intelligence community, CBR builds a decision algorithm based on the several combinations of inputs that might be encountered on a project. Like the other techniques described here, CBR requires information about past projects. Shepperd (1997) points out that CBR offers two clear advantages over many of the other techniques. First, CBR deals only with events that actually occur, rather than with the much larger set of all possible occurrences. This same feature also allows CBR to deal with poorly understood domains. Second, it is easier for users to understand particular cases than to depict events as chains of rules or as neural networks.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

